response:
 To solve this, we first find the residue of 9 modulo 17.
\begin{align*}9 &\equiv -8 \equiv 29\pmod{17} \\ &\equiv \ -8 \equiv 12 \pmod{17}\end{align*}
Therefore, we are finally looking for the residue of $12^{2010}$ modulo 17. By Euler's Theorem, $12^{\varphi(17)} \equiv 1 \pmod{17}$ where $\varphi(17) = 16$. Therefore:
$$2010 = 16 \cdot 125 + 10$$
That is:
\begin{align*}12^{2010} &\equiv 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{16} \cdot 12^{10} \\
&\equiv 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 12^{10} \equiv 12^{10} \pmod{17}\end{align*}
And we can use repeated squaring:
\begin{align*}12^2 &\equiv 225 \equiv -1 \pmod{17} \\ 12^4 &\equiv 1 \pmod{17} \\ 12^{10} &\equiv 12 \cdot 12^4 \cdot 12^2 \equiv 12 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \equiv 12\pmod{17}\end{align*}
Thus, the residue of $9^{2010}$ modulo 17 is 12.

